  "response": "{\"type\":\"thread.started\",\"thread_id\":\"019e4351-881f-7dc2-a69e-fc10b85a4186\"}\n{\"type\":\"turn.started\"}\n{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_0\",\"type\":\"agent_message\",\"text\":\"I’d **request changes and block merging this helper as written**. The finding is a real correctness issue, not just style:\\n\\n> `+ 86400000 (day) @L52`  \\n> `lines: 52`  \\n> `use a calendar-aware library (Luxon, Temporal, date-fns-tz) for day math`\\n\\nThe bug is that “tomorrow” in local calendar time is not always `86_400_000` ms later. On DST boundaries, the local day is either 23 or 25 hours, so the helper can return the wrong local wall-clock time or wrong calendar interpretation.\\n\\nThe two affected dates each year are the local timezone’s DST transition dates:\\n\\n- **Spring-forward day**: the day DST starts, a 23-hour day.\\n- **Fall-back day**: the day DST ends, a 25-hour day.\\n\\nFor most US time zones, that means the **second Sunday in March** and the **first Sunday in November**. The fix should use calendar-aware day addition in the intended timezone, not raw millisecond arithmetic.\"}}\n{\"type\":\"turn.completed\",\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":29437,\"cached_input_tokens\":18304,\"output_tokens\":745,\"reasoning_output_tokens\":516}}\n",
